		<description><![CDATA[Two sent me thisÂ LINKÂ and I&#8217;ve been reading a few of them here and there in between my regular internet musings. It has the &#8220;last words&#8221; of prisoners as they are being executed. Of all the things that they could say, the topics are either God or family. They don&#8217;t say things like, &#8220;I wish I <a class="more-link" href="http://www.brandyborges.com/?p=110">Continue reading <i class="fa fa-chevron-right"></i></a>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Two sent me thisÂ <a href="http://www.goodbyewarden.com/" target="_blank">LINK</a>Â and I&#8217;ve been reading a few of them here and there in between my regular internet musings. It has the &#8220;last words&#8221; of prisoners as they are being executed. Of all the things that they could say, the topics are either God or family. They don&#8217;t say things like, &#8220;I wish I could have golfed one more round&#8221; or &#8220;I would have liked to have gotten that certain job&#8221; they are saying the names of loved ones, they are telling family that they loved them and then they say that they will see their loved ones when they join them some day.<br />
It brings all of the recent stress and countless things that I bear on my shoulders to an easy focus of what is important: my God and my family. Those two points echo the exact words of the evangelist that spoke at our church last week. When all the busyness and chaos rush by us each day and it seems like the days just mimic the last one without a discernibleÂ difference, I need to bring my focus back to where it needs to be.</p>
